Russian President Vladimir Putin has signed a law imposing administrative liability for the violation of the time and procedure for payment of goods (work, services) in procurement for State and municipal needs.
The Act is intended to address the very acute problem of non-performance by employers in public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation in which entrepreneurs were unable to obtain payment under existing State and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Office of the Procurator-General of the Russian Federation to take the problem into special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not deal with unscrupulous employers who had entered into unfunded contracts, tried to avoid paying obligations and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, 9,700 submissions have been submitted by the Public Prosecutor ' s Office in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, with the result that 4,500 officials have been disciplined and 533 administrative officers, and 75 materials have been submitted to the investigative bodies for the purpose of organizing the procedural checks, 46 of which have been prosecuted.
As a result, more than 66 billion roubles were owed to entrepreneurs.
These huge sums have not been accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion-dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts have led to huge debts.
Here's the case.
The head of a small company won a competition for social transport services for several million roubles.
The man invested all his working money, fully met his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is an increasing financial coma of salaries, taxes, loans that would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought the assistance of the prosecutor's office.
The problem has now been maximized in a number of regions.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total debt on State and municipal contracts identified by the procurators of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation was about 27.4 billion roubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the Public Prosecutor ' s Office operates in a manual crisis management regime.
The Attorney-General personally holds visiting meetings with representatives of the local authorities, at which all violations revealed by the procurators are dealt with in a substantive manner and measures taken to address them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already taken place this year in Jaroslavla and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of Federal Act No. 189-FZ on the amendment of the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation on the establishment of the administrative liability of the employer's officials for the violation of the time and procedure for the payment of goods (work, services) in the procurement of public and municipal needs, signed by the President of the Russian Federation last week, will improve the public customer's pay discipline.
The draft law was drafted by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Attorney-General ' s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offences with an article which provides for a fine of 30,000 to 50,000 roubles for breaching the time limit and the procedure for payment of goods, works and services by an official of the employer in State and municipal procurement.
If an official had already been administratively punished for a similar offence, he would be disqualified for a period of between one and two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure that these legislative innovations are applied in practice.
Civil Rights Unit announced a travel warning in Missouri.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People issued a warning to colored people travelling to Missouri because of discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
