It was only in 2015 that Freeport produced about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua can boast forest reserves estimated at $78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuas, guaranteeing that the powerful Indonesian armed forces retain their suffocating presence here.
According to an investigation into The New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local troops and units, up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuas threaten the existence of this golden vein and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, more than 500,000 Papuas have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969 and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the massacres in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the 1970s could be considered genocide.
Last year alone, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything”, a report published in 2016 by the Brisbane diocese contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture – especially, as stated in another report, rape and electric shocks – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It is hard to count the number of victims because the incidents occur every week,” says Andreas Harrison, researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
Gaiks have been protracted as Papua's resources have attracted the influx of displaced persons from other parts of Indonesia.
The 3.5-million population of the province is 83 per cent Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants from densely populated Indonesian islands – Java, Sumatra, and Sulawesi – arrive.
Yavan shops, “warungi”, sell fried chicken and a mixture of gado-gado vegetables served with peanut sauce.
