“This has resulted in the loss of the market for indigenous Papuans, Mother-Mama (Women) of Papua.”
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, known as the Jokovi people, vowed to address inequalities and violations of rights in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the President's Palace in Jakarta, a former carpenter obtained support from 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But there has been little change in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to meet our hopes for justice,” Yow says.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Jokowi Paniai suffered a tragedy.
