The frightened children told them they should turn on the lights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebay, one soldier was offended by their tone and later returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased children and beat them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julianus Emo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a government office nearby, and the next day, the situation escalated.
About a thousand pope men, women and children gathered in a football field in front of the local police station and the military command centre to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed the White, the pago dance of the popuas, running in circles and playing bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation escalated, the soldiers were ordered on the internal radio link to “If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them”, as claimed in an official document that was seen by Time magazine correspondents but not published in the local media.
The 50 - year - old Jeremias Kayama, head of the Kogo Koto district in Enarotali, felt the danger and called for calm, asking the crowd to leave their homes.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned around, I suddenly had a bullet in my left wrist,” he told Time magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who shot him, but he says the bullet came from the shreng of the soldiers gathered.
"There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots," he adds.
A local resident of Alfius Jowa was shot three times, as his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, tells us.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johns, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told the magazine “TIME.”
"I saw him dead... I kissed him."
General Yotge Mende, Chief Inspector of the Papua Police, told reporters that his officers were merely "protecting" their base because it was attacked.
