Then Viranto declined to speak to the magazine “TIME” on 5 June in Jakarta and said that he did not plan to establish an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, "All will be decided through the courts."
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of “crimes against humanity” in connection with the death of more than 1,000 people during the bloody East Timor independence vote in 1999, said that 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
