But when Roger was put on a loop around his neck, almost all the viewers really held their breath.
Since 2005, activists have returned to the Morse Ford Bridge to replay the night that the puppets lynched two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcolm, and George and May Murray Dorsey, in 1946.
No one was convicted of these murders.
"It's amazing that in all these years no one has been arrested -- although we see them next to us; although we know who they are," says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the performance.
"It's a stain on our history and it's a stone on our souls."
71-year-old Brooks is a former member of the Georgia Congress, who's been fighting for human rights all his life.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the people of Monroe that injustice has never been corrected.
"We want investigations, we want closure, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice," he says.
"We can't go to healing and reconciliation until we get justice."
The coroner covers the body of one of the lynching victims at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI reports received by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighbouring counties were suspected of involvement in lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although suspects have remained at large for decades, human rights defenders say that in the city, two linked motives of vigilantes were always well known: politics and sex.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court ' s ruling allowed for the first time black citizens to vote on the primary that was due to take place in the summer.
About the same election, according to the FBI, black user Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, white landowner, apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says that according to rumours in town, Hester slept with his wife, Malcolm Dorothy, and that the baby she was supposed to have wasn't from her husband.
According to FBI reports, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $600 in bail to get Malcolm out of prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they were driving from prison and coming up to the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of vigilantes surrounded the car.
"It turns out that he organized and directed Harrison's murders," that's what the FBI has to say in a report.
"It is also clear that there was a conspiracy between state and city law enforcement agencies that not only took part in the murders but also destroyed the evidence and concealed the identity of the witnesses."
Brooks calls it shorter.
"It was an attempt at voting rights," he says.
"They were all killed to send a message to the blacks in town: if you register and vote, you'll be the same."
For almost ten years, Cassandra Greene runs an annual show that reproduces that lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is glaring, he captures the audience and speaks of the deep racism that many would like to believe is no longer in America.
It's hard to see and even harder to turn around, but Green thinks that's what matters.
"We don't want to talk about Lynch's courts because they show us our own uglyness," she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I've been through."
This year's rehearsal began in June, and on the first day, almost 30 actors -- a dozen whites, the rest of the blacks -- gathered in the room and listened to the years-old review of the play.
Wade Marbo was a director with Greene.
He's been the main member of the clan for years, but he says it's never been easier.
"I think I'm dirty because it's not the man I am," says Marbo.
"But I think it's very important to remember this story because we don't want to go back at that time."
Indoor actors Darrios Bradshaw and Nick Ruscon, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, repeat their roles.
Spectal starts with Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife, Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Screaming back to Ruscon.
There's a blow.
And at the same time, everyone (at least all black actors) gets a laugh.
Green laughs louder than anyone else.
"What's going on" asks Ascon.
He's concerned and embarrassed.
Am I overreacting?
"No," says Greene through the laughter.
"I just don't think white people said nigga."
"Yes, yes," laughs one of the black performers.
"You have to say hard 'r'."
And the energy in the room is changing, and discomfort is changing with the sense of partnership.
Everyone has to do the right thing, not just for the play, but for the memory of the four dead.
The scene starts over.
This time, when Ruscona says the word "n," it's clear and sharp.
No man laughs.
The play ends violently and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of actors and sings Billy Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is broken through a word.
A hundred yards away, half a dozen viewers are wiped out of their eyes with tears and sweat.
There's almost the same number of blacks and whites among the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York, to watch the show; many live very close.
They all endured Georgia's heavy perfume for almost eight hours while Brooks led them to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until now, the murder has remained history, but now that they're standing in the same place as lynching people, it seems like their ghosts are in the air right now.
When the last note of the song is silenced, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
The children bow to their heads, touch the blood paint, and the stationary bodies, and whisper to each other.
"They're not really dead," a little boy murmuring, as if to remind himself.
In a few minutes, Greene thanks the audience, and all of a sudden it's over.
Actors throw ropes off their necks and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the main doll.
Nick Ruscona hugs two other actors and suddenly, weeping, falls into their arms: the emotional stress of the performance finally hit him.
"It's all right," whispers one of the women.
"We know you have a good heart.
You had your reasons for that."
Later, the audience sits down for dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta lively discusses the performance with the black couple they just met.
Denisa Daplinsky barely finds words to describe how she feels after the show.
"It's hard to listen to these horrible, scary words and actions... people who look like you, and who do it because they look like you," she says.
