Recent tests of asylum-seekers in Sweden, who were subjected to a new medical age assessment method, show that more than 80 per cent of the tests were assessed as persons over 18 years of age, but not all trust the accuracy of the results.
The Swedish National Forensic Medicine Agency (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age assessment in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the real age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published 2,481 tests between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty per cent (2002) of the tests were estimated to be 18 years old or older, and in another 25 cases, the forensics agency estimated that the test was “probably 18 years old or older”.
In the case of 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was “probably less than 18”.
Tests are carried out only in cases where the age of a person is questionable.
According to Johan Guernsson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent with those of the past months.
“We don't see much difference in statistics over the past months, the numbers are quite appropriate,” he said to the “The Local” portal.
The high proportion of cases in which persons were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, it was “most likely to be 18 years old or older”.
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases, a person had openly stated that 18 were being implemented this year.
The medical age assessment method of X-raying the teeth of wisdom and tomography of the knee joints and giving them to dentists and radiologists has also led to criticism in some authorities.
One of the skeptics is an endocrinologist from the Caroline Institute, Claude Marcus, whose work includes assessing human biological maturity to determine whether they have experienced puberty before or later.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think we should use the measurement methods that are being used now.
The biological age is thus very inaccurate.
If we cannot define it with certainty, we should not pretend to do what we can,” he said to the newspaper Metro.
However, Göransen, from the Forensic Medicine Agency, argued in favour of the accuracy of the tests: “In general, the risk of mistaking a child as an adult is low.
We face the greatest risk when the human being is about 18 years old, in which case it is about 10 per cent.”
