Judges Offer protection from Presidents
On behalf of Vladimir Putin, the Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC) has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC suggests that the powers of the presidents of the courts should be limited and that they should be elected.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wishes to introduce special districts which will not be linked to territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court is also required to present its presidential proposals.
The HRC has finalized proposals that will enhance the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on 3 January 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with the Council.
The meeting with the Council on 8 December 2016 included individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see OS of 9 December).
The work of the HRC has resulted in 25 proposals, covering both issues of ensuring the independence of the judiciary and the identification of judicial errors, as well as the financing of the courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Cremlian human rights defenders is to limit the powers of court presidents to enhance the independence of the rest of the judiciary.
If the candidate for the post of judge had successfully passed the competition and had received the support of the judicial community, the President of the Court, in the opinion of the Human Rights Council, should submit him for appointment without the right to refuse, as currently permitted by law.
It is also proposed that the President should not be allowed to allocate cases between judges.
Doing it, experts admit, can be a specially written computer program.
The HRC also considers that the President is not entitled to “predetermine the results of the judge's qualification, initiate disciplinary action, or decide on the imposition of additional material payments”.
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to the “election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and to “power them for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation”.
All presidents of the courts (from republic to district) are now appointed by the President for a period of six years at the request of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes to re-organize the appeal and cassation before the courts of general jurisdiction.
Their structure is now linked to administrative territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC states that “there is a need to ensure that individual courts of appeal and cassation are organized, not at the level of the regional courts in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts”.
The experts are guided by the practice of arbitral tribunals.
There are “judiciary districts” which do not coincide with administrative division in the Russian Federation, but which thus guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who find it difficult to use “telephone law”.
The HRC peace judges propose to be strengthened by people's jurors to deal with certain “civil and administrative categories” with them.
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement at work, protection of honour and dignity, denial of driving rights, etc.
"These are only our proposals," explained HRC member, retired Constitutional Court judge Tamara Morsjakov.
She also recalled that the President ' s mandate concerned not only the HRC but also the Supreme Court (JCJ), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time to carry out the task (including the Office of the Attorney-General and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To inform Vladimir Putin of the effectiveness of the independence of justice in the Russian Federation, President Vyacheslav Lebedev is scheduled to do so by 1 September.
Living a high life: half-storys and crafty designs turned this little apartment into a spacious home in Earls Court.
Joan Lee, a former banker interested in real estate repairs, moved from a large house in Nightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a pretty model home like Queen Anne, and in favor of the new design, it says that Joan didn't pack her things and moved again.
"I used to live with my ex-boyfriend in Knightsbridge in a much larger area," Joan says.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
They showed me this apartment at Earls Court, and there were also high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price on the same day."
Since the first view, the 1,000 square feet flat has been renovated.
Originally, it was an apartment with one bedroom of complex planning – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage spaces and half floors to extract the maximum benefit from the generous height of the ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
That was my demand," she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Notting Hill architectural design studio "Duck & Shed" to use ceilings 12.5 feet high and build a home that would not only be a successful project but would be for Joan to live.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two spaces above each other, so the architectural challenge was to create a semi-storey where you could stand in full growth.
Erfan had to think creatively to handle the breeze.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult”, he explains.
“We had to place the premises so that they would be one over the other, and we didn't have to bend.
It was not just a simple platform that needed to be built, but to bend the structure to the right height and allow the use of the spaces from the top and bottom.”
This decision enabled Erfan to set up two full-sized rooms one above the other in the space reserved, and a lot more interesting.
From the semi-deck through the vintage copper light window, the Retrouvius opens a view of the luxurious living room below.
Mirror furniture with gold finishes, silver accents, and vintage lighting from Serge Muy set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding sight, space, and light.
The short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, a mirror protection panel seems like a window to another room.
At the entrance, the mirror closets are used to store all of Joan's dishes.
To create a sense of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block the kitchen when it is not used.
There's nothing new about the folding kitchens.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it's a moving door upside down, like in the garage.
“The engineering was involved here,” Erfan tells us about the reinforced steel wood-fibrous shield door.
“It is equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.”
Thanks to the reasonable use of storage space and facilities, Joan received an additional 16 square metres, an additional bedroom, and improved planning.
“In the end, the floor area is exactly what you're going to sell, that is, what your real estate is worth,” Erfan says.
“Speaking harshly, a real estate agent will enter and make calculations on the basis of the floor space.”
Here they have been able to increase the floor area using quality materials that give a shade of luxurious space.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection to home,” Erfan says.
“No one falls in love with electrical wiring in the walls.
It is important, but it does not touch the strings of our hearts.”
This shows that with good design and an enlarged metre, an apartment can turn from something normal into something amazing.
Actually, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
