Brothers fight for a real estate empire worth more than $500 million.
Two brothers fight for one of Victoria's largest real estate empires worth over $500 million – 40 years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former director of Carlton Football Club and developer Colin de Lutis lives at the Torak Palace three doors from his younger brother Paul, who filed a claim against him in the Supreme Court for the division of possessions and assets.
Paul wants to get out of the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court still has a violent dispute about divorce.
Together with their mother, Anna's brothers own 87 facilities worth more than half a billion dollars, purchased since their family bought a shop on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew up in a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's property list today includes office buildings, construction sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Golden Coast and Mount Bueller, and suburb shopping centres.
In agreement with the late father, Colin - whom Paul describes as the “primary driving force and dominant person” of the De Lutis family - owns about two thirds of the company's assets and Paul owns about one third.
According to the court, this means that Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's property is 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
"The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of property," he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several failed attempts at reconciliation, the Supreme Court heard its first hearing.
The brothers are now arguing about who will control the existing business - from which Paul thinks Colin expelled him.
Colin claims this is not the case, but he accuses Paul of incompetent management of certain sites.
In Colin's testimony at the beginning of the trial, he says he hopes to resolve the dispute.
"My Italian roots make me consider the family the highest priority," he wrote.
Court fees are rising as a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, e-mails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Kramer; both parties have attracted the most prominent lawyers, including Royal Advocate Allan Meyers, and the best cookers.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late wife, Luigi, were immigrants from Italy; since the late 1950s, they have run dairy bars and malls, and in the early 1970s they bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood where Colin opened the first family jeans store.
Colin says he launched Westco when he was "in the last grade of the school, and Paul was a boy (about 10 years old)."
Anna De Lutis says that he and Luigi, who died in 2012, were hoping to hand over their property to their sons without conflict.
"Louigi used to tell me that he didn't want the brothers to judge in court," she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of De Lucis' group; Colina says that Mark got 10 million when he left the business, and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "dissatisfied with the financial conditions of their division."
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of AFL's board of directors and, according to his 2015 biography, Eddie McGuire was the best friend of a TV star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin responded with a text message saying that since the case had not yet been tried, "I really have nothing to say."
"I'm very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to sue me and talk to the court about our family's name," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in his statement that he was trying to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father doesn't want to see Paul and me arguing in court," he said, adding, "still hopes for a solution to the conflict."
On Friday, that hope must have dissipated.
"The judgment in our case will soon be rendered by the court," wrote Colin.
The new chief of Trump's office is planning to limit the information to the president.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly can really do it.
In that case, he'll be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House Chief of Staff is planning to limit the flow of information to President Trump, including news reports from the media, hoping to keep the chief calmer.
That's what reporter Josh Dozee says.
"At a meeting held by the new Chief of Staff of the White House, John F. Kelly, with the management of the staff on his first day of business, he outlined the main problem in the White House of President Donald Trump, which he hopes to solve: bad channels of information to the President."
Kelly told the staff that the information should go through it -- paper or briefing -- because the president would be better off making decisions if he received the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is absolutely correct, but others have already failed in trying to control Trump by tracking his information.
President Trump's relationship with television developed decades ago -- and now that he's in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still strong.
“When Trump, as a candidate, resented the unfair coverage of the campaign, it was useful to show him that he received fair coverage in publications that could be reconvinced,” said "Politico" in February, Sam Nanberg, a former electoral staff adviser.
Tara Palmeri wrote to Politico at the time that "six former members of the electoral staff said that in order to control Trump's habit of tweeting, they had to make sure that there was a constant flow of praise in the personal information he received."
Okay.
But the idea that Trump's habit of tweeting was ever "under control" is ridiculous.
Maybe these election staff members know something that we don't know -- for example, that if it weren't for them, Trump's tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about the tweets Trump didn't publish.
If his staff had saved him from trouble at least a few times, their efforts had not been in vain.
But no one has ever managed to keep Trump from putting oil into the fire.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agendas by supplying Trump with material, reliable or not, which confirms their views.
Politico, just about this story, wrote in May about the tendency of the councillors to keep telling the president questionable information.
Here's an example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Trump's current and former staff say that Trump can react very sharply to negative reports in the press, especially those containing dangerous leaks of information, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
This happened at the end of February, when someone gave the president a copy of an article from GotNews.com, the website of the Internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Cathy Welsh was accused of standing behind the leaks in the White House.
It doesn't matter that Johnson is forever tampered with on Twitter for his aggressive behavior, that he didn't present specific facts, or that in the past he launched false accusations and then turned them down.
Trump read the article and started asking staff about Welsh."
Goldmacher adds that the then Chief of Staff Raines Pribus and the Secretary of Staff Rob Porter "were trying to build a system to control and document the flow of paper that Trump receives."
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly's trying to do the same.
He may be a more effective manager than Pribus, but Trump is still impulsive, and his assistants are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
The Tumen Prosecutor's Office is fighting the HIV dissident.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office challenged the ruling of the Kalininsky Riyud of Tumeni, who had dropped the criminal case against a local woman who had died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died because the mother was a HIV dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court relieved her of responsibility for reconciliation with her father.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office considers that the crime cannot be left unpunished without setting a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against a Tumeni resident was initiated under article 109, paragraph 1, of the Criminal Code (death due to negligence) in April, following the death of her three-year-old daughter from HIV infection.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
“The woman was not treated herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that there was no HIV infection”, explained the Tumen district prosecutor's office.
The criminal case was brought to the Kalininsky Rye Court of Tumeni, which decided on 25 July to discontinue it.
The father of the deceased girl pleaded, explaining that “he has forgiven his wife, has no claim against her, has made amends and has apologized”.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office disagreed with the court ' s decision and filed an appeal, demanding that the dismissal order be revoked and that it be referred to a new hearing.
The girl died, and there's no way to make amends for the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the advice of the doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her against a dangerous infection”, reported the Public Prosecutor's Office.
According to the oversight body, she should be punished, otherwise other HIV dissidents would follow her example.
According to the Tumen AIDS Center, there are now about 12 children living with HIV in Tumen province who are not receiving treatment because of parental refusal.
"And this situation has already improved -- in the year of a special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat children with HIV have changed their minds -- they have allowed for diagnostics, they have started taking medications," said the Spokesperson of the AIDS Center, Elena Lozaev.
According to her, it was not possible to influence parents in a legislative manner, and as a result not all HIV-positive children were found, mothers were not allowed to examine them, were hiding and were running away with children from hospitals.
The Hazards of HIV Dissenters
At the end of last year, Petroburg's sociologists presented the results of the first study of the so-called HIV dissident movement in Russia.
HIV dissidents are called people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Health professionals and activists in AIDS service NCBs call such views anti-medical, and their spread is seen as a serious threat.
