The Gypsies overcame the trench and returned to the "millionaire street"
Some of the richest landlords in West Midland are again in conflict with the strong Roma who have overcame the moats that have been dug by the municipal authorities in order to re-enter the field near their homes.
The Gypsies parked 20 houses on wheels in a field bordering the rich Solihalla street, which received the funny name "Millionaire Street".
With horses, infants, and lots of wheelhouses, they returned after being kicked out no later than in May, and were not prevented by the moats dug by the municipal authorities to prevent their invasion.
This tactful company found a break in the defense structures and shredded its vehicles through a section that left unsolved to leave the path.
The angry residents attacked the city of Solihal, saying that it was “unable to solve the problem.”
An anonymous local woman said, "They came here Monday night after they were driven out of Bentley Heath, where they threw stones at passers-by."
The municipality should be shamed and forced to act because it is completely incapable of solving the problem.
The gypsies were here in May, they were banished, and they came back again.
More gypsies arrived last night, and maybe even more today.
“The municipality of Birmingham knows how to solve this problem, they get long-term court orders to protect their parks,” she added.
I live on Streetsbrook Road, and I don't like that I keep paying municipal tax, and the municipality can't even stop it.”
A local resident who wanted to stay anonymous said, "This is ridiculous, we just saw these gypsies leave the previous time, and here, please, this attack continues."
This time, there were more, and we even saw a horse walking in the meadow.”
A representative of the municipality of Solihallah stated: “We are aware of an illegal camp on land near Streetsbrook Road and are cooperating with the Solihal police; we are taking the necessary legal action to drive them away as soon as possible.”
To help us gather evidence, it is essential that as many locals as possible report any antisocial or criminal behavior to the police on the phone 101.
This gives us an idea of the situation that the court will consider when we present our case to them.
