Italy is tightening its tone with regard to NGO ships that rescue migrants.
Italy warned NGOs owned by rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they would not be able to continue unless they complied with the new regulations governing their activities.
“If NGOs fail to comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to tell whether they will be able to continue their activities”, said Home Secretary Mario Minniti in an interview with the Turkish daily Stampa.
The warning was given by Minnichi the day after the Italian authorities confiscated a vessel belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rette on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has worked for only a year, has declined to comment on the substance of the detailed charges brought against it by the Italian prosecutor Ambrojo Kartozio.
"For us, saving human life is and will remain the highest priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue to operate in the search and rescue zone," states the organization's statement on social media.
"We will only be able to assess all the charges that have been brought now after we have gathered all the information and can assess the situation."
The Italian authorities have been following the Juventa ship, owned by Jugend Retette, since October.
His crew is suspected of having taken migrants on board by lifeboats, who were sent directly to them by traffickers, and allowing smugglers to leave with boats they could use again.
At least one such meeting was supposed to take place only 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, as stated in the prosecution file, the content of which was published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the orders of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in the area, for humanitarian reasons rather than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct presupposes, mainly, that the “Juventa” type of vessels will have on board an Italian police officer to oversee their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue have agreed to comply with the code: Save the Children, Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Open embraced from Spain.
The latter stated on Thursday that it considered the new regulations unnecessary but acceptable, provided that they did not entail any “significant change or interference” with its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is the Nobel Prize-winning MSF.
Meanwhile, Minnichi said that the sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicated that efforts to support the Libyan Coast Guard and cooperation with local mayors were bearing fruit.
"In the last days we began to see light at the end of the tunnel," said the minister.
He reported on plans for further negotiations with the Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
