The authorities of the Russian Federation have recently significantly intensified their policies in the Libyan direction and, with visits to Moscow, delegations of the opposing Libyan parties have become more active.
The head of the Russian contact group on the intra-Libyan settlement of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, Assistant Head of the Chechen Republic, Lev Degov, told us what the objectives of Moscow in the region were and on whom he was betting.
The contact group on Libya, which you are chairing, is almost unknown.
Let's say the contact group on Ukraine -- everybody knows about it.
And here is a veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The Contact Group was established at the initiative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma.
Its activities are overseen by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimhanov.
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma, Vyacheslav Volodin.
The reason for the formation of the group was the detention in Libya of a Russian tanker, Mechanique Chebotarev (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board).
We've been thinking about how to help the crew.
At that time, a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma, supported by Head of Chechnya Ramzan Qadirov, was established.
How come you were the one who led her?
Since I have been working on Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the group.
Our activities have not been limited to the release of sailors from Chebotarev's Mechanic.
We were able to establish contacts with representatives of all the major factions opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - and from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government led by Faiz Saraj is based) and Tobrook (the parliamentary section that opposes the Government and supports Marshal Khalifa Khaftar, who controls the eastern parts of Libya).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (the Libyan Vice-Prime Minister) we were able to quickly negotiate the release of Russian sailors.
It was then decided to make more effective use of these contacts, to establish a contact group.
Its task is to analyse the situation, identify key factors and players, and engage with all parties to the conflict.
I wish to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with either side of the conflict; we are engaged in dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group and how many are in Libya on a permanent basis?
The contact group is now composed of five persons.
Among them are people with experience in the security forces, including the Ministry of Defence.
We also wish to include in the team of specialists in the region, representatives of the Institute of the Middle East Rana.
There is no permanent presence of any of our staff in Libya, which is not yet necessary.
Is there any Russian military advisors, instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group includes ex-military personnel...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
Like when we go to hot spots.
Or cities that have been closed to a certain point for us, such as Misurata (where militias are based, which have played a role in overthrowing Libyan leader Muammar Qaddafi in 2011 and which have increased significantly in the years to come).
We arrived in Misurata in January this year.
We were scared, told that there were Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there ourselves, to examine the real military potential, who was responsible for what the rumours were about, what the real role of Islamists was.
In Misurat, we met with all the members of the units that were involved in the destruction of the IG in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was taken away from the Russian-prohibited “Islamic State” - UO).
We wanted to see them, meet these people, check out information that they played a decisive role in the destruction of the IG in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these to himself.
And what conclusion did you come to?
Is it not Haftar who won the Islamic State in Libya?
He didn't do it.
Haftar had operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And the IG in Sirte was fought by the structures that were subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And by the way, we've invited to Russia the people who did this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived -- the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, and the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in Douma, MIDE, and Rosgwardia.
You, as we understand it, are in all Libyan regions, and you are probably imagining the moods of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections that Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj reached at the end of July in Paris?
Or again, as has been the case many times in the past, agreements will be broken down, hostilities will resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
The fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting has been a good signal to us, not long ago.
In the recent past, both leaders have been very negative about each other.
And as for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Khaftara, and many believe it.
We were faced with this situation when we were in Misurat, and Haftar was on the same day on board a Russian carrier, Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misurat, they didn't believe in coincidence.
They said, "You must be very brave people who came to us today."
But our challenge is to show that we do not support only Khaftar, we are engaged in a dialogue with all the key players in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar spoke.
Does understanding with Russian partners at the human, emotional level make it easier for him to study twice in the USSR?
And, by the way, does Haftar speak Russian?
If he knows Russian, it's very relative.
But the fact that he learned from us, of course, makes it easier to talk to him.
And by the way, it's not just him.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misurat, we meet the generals who studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And now they speak Russian very well.
And they're reaching for Russia, and they're kind of nostalgic about it.
Do you consider the immediate lifting of the arms embargo imposed on Libya to be possible?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
Interested, of course, but, as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict, and we do not want to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
With regard to the arms embargo, there have been constant calls from the Libyans for Russia to contribute in some way to its lifting.
The process of constitution-making is now well under way in Libya.
We hope that the parties will reach compromises and reach an internal consensus.
Then the election will take place, as was said at the Saraj and Haftara meetings.
If elections are held and legitimate power is finally elected (and none of the parties now has that status), the question of lifting the arms embargo can be raised in the UN Council.
It is pointless and dangerous to raise this issue now, only to escalate the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, felt abandoned by EU allies.
Can Moscow, in this situation, help Italian partners by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is it that the Haftar forces will take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers moving immigrants to Europe?
That's a very timely question.
We're actively working on it.
The Italians need Russia’s support because Moscow engages in dialogue at the same time with Haftar, Saraj, Misurata, and the south.
The tribes in southern Libya play a major role in this matter, and they are prepared to cooperate with Russia.
Is this about preventing the flow of migrants in the South in long-distance?
You mean, on the contrary, they're turning back the buses that Nigerian migrants are driving in?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in continuing these flows.
We hope to help unite the South in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes of the South.
But first, we would like to see a consensus on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is regarded as an Islamist, a supporter of the implementation of sharia in the country.
How radical is he?
Would that not be an obstacle to establishing relations with Russia or the West?
I'll tell you my personal opinion of him.
In my view, he is opposed to radical Islam.
But Islamists are part of his coalition.
Yes, but it is his own position that Libya must be a perfectly normal country - a moderately Islamic, open world.
And he's also actively fighting terrorists.
How did he get that reputation?
It is created by those countries that do not want Russia to communicate with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, and there is a legislative, executive and judicial power.
There's a national oil corporation, a national bank and other government structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in keeping us out of it.
And we mixed up all the cards with them and started to interact actively with both Tripoli and Tobrook.
We are already reaping the benefits of this work: Rosneft has concluded a cooperation agreement with the Libyan oil company, NOC.
The director of NOC, Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosnefti's head, Igor Sechin, made a deal, is directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, there was the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess we'll re-sell.
What other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
Plans to re-sign the contracts concluded at Muammar Gaddafi.
These include, inter alia, previous transport agreements (railway construction), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have anything to pay for?
Well, they have oil.
So this is, like Iran, the oil-for-service scheme?
I don't know what the pattern will be, I don't do these things directly.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We're basically doing peacekeeping work there.
For us, it is important to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans negotiate with one another so that they can establish order and Libya has ceased to be an enabling environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, that is the main task to help the Libyan people and push the terrorists out of there.
Do you have any data on the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that, to date, no one from Russia or other countries of the former USSR is there.
He said that he had about 50,000 phone records of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya - OS) and no Russian speech there.
Which states are these fighters then?
I don't want to go into that detail.
Then we'll put the question differently.
How many of the Islamic militants in Libya are the Libyans themselves?
There are virtually no Libyans among them, not more than 5 per cent.
The rest are incoming.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks on the example of Paris?
That's the plan.
We are engaged in intensive negotiations with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have offered to visit Moscow or Grozny again.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say right now.
Several visits have yet to take place, and I hope that the time and place of the talks will be clarified.
