Astronomers have found a hell of a planet where even iron can melt.
After a first study of the stratospheric properties of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, astrophysics were greatly surprised by its temperature, which is capable of evaporating iron and other metals.
Experts have noticed that water molecules are so warmed up by the light of the star that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble Telescope has captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant, which is a high temperature that causes water in the planet's atmosphere to glow infrared range.
WASP-121b refers to so-called hot Jupiters, gas giants, in size and mass comparable to the largest planet of the solar system, but tens of times closer to the parent star.
It only lasts a year on an exoplanet with 1.3 Earth days, and its gas casing has been heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change threatens the lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and South France, but there are now fears that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavanda has grown worse because of dry weather and insect disease; this has caused constant headaches for scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Eric Shes, an expert from the Provence agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM, says, "Lavanda in Provence is indeed at risk because in recent years the plant has been experiencing the effects of climate change: in the spring and especially in the fall, the rains have decreased considerably.
It affects the life span of the lavender.
And there are little cicades that jump over leaves of insects that carry microbacteria; in very dry weather, there are a lot of them."
