Starts that will help your company avoid becoming another Uber.
Aimee Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among his startup staff in the area of electronic commerce, but the polls didn't work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, untrue.
And even though she promised anonymity, some staff members did not trust the process.
“He has never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, the manager of a 75-person San Francisco-based company called Madison Reed, which deals with electronic hair-care trade.
She therefore sought assistance from third parties.
A new type of start-up in the area of personnel is emerging, helping companies to find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software that is designed to measure staff involvement, they allow companies to make rapid inquiries, to refer to certain teams and population groups, to offer staff anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and, in some cases, to allow informants to pass the top management and direct contact with the directorate.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, and where is Fitbit for your company?" says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint startup in Redwood City, whose analytical programs are used by companies to measure employee involvement.
Errett said that she had gained a better understanding of what her employees thought and felt in three years of Glint use.
In addition to the express polls and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers the company's heat map and illustrates which units have more complaints and which managers have a low rating of approval, which allows it to understand why.
Companies realize a little bit that they need to control the workplace, or they will become another Uber, who was involved in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog describing the aggressive environment in which those who were dissatisfied were punished.
For start-ups like "Glint", this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for profitable businesses.
The “Let's Talk About Pay” Internet portal, dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global governance, regulation and alignment industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The "Convercent" launch from Denver, Colorado, to help companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year against the background of the fall in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has almost 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has recently emerged as a client.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized feedback interviews, collect confidential answers in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows staff to report misconduct.
And if the top manager gets involved, the complaints go straight to the directorate.
“The Court of Public Opinion has seized power from the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is ill-treated or unethical, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of client boycotts, staff outflows and lawsuits, Queenlan reported.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, used Convercent for over a year to make sure that the staff were aware of the rules and procedures, and to suggest a simple way to contact the company's headquarters.
Previously, if the staff member wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for a telephone number or a head office e-mail, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, reported James Vitrano, the head of the legal office of Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to monitor staff grievances.
Now that the company uses the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, charisma and unfair pay – can be quickly detected and addressed.
“I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of staff,” said Vitrano, who leads the Risk Management Team of Ruby Today.
“And we protect our shareholders from litigation with staff.”
According to Queenland, companies began to take the ethics, values and involvement of employees more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed because of ethical irregularities as a result of the Dela Enron.
But it was only when “social networks became widespread” that companies realized that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from spreading the virus online.
“Before starting to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both "Glint" and "Convercent" offer their software as a service, charging companies regularly to use their products.
It's a business model and an opportunity with the approval of venture investors who supported both startups.
In February, "Convercent" received funding of $10 million from firms such as "Sapphire Ventures" and "Tola Capital", bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Besser Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing volume of research shows that today's employees expect more of their jobs than they did before.
In markets with strong competition, such as the Silicon Valley, high wages, and interesting projects, they are just the minimum necessary.
The employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated and that they devote their time to companies with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in a company, feel that they are being heard, and that the work they do is producing results, they are more keen to make such a company a success,” says Nina McQueen, Vice President for Global Benefits and Satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors earn income when companies from their portfolio are doing well; business from companies is doing well when employees are loyal and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase the dedication and involvement of staff, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to culture experts in the workplace, it is important to have data on staff involvement.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks for feedback from its employees, it may give the impression that change is coming.
And if change doesn't come fast enough, or if it doesn't come at all, there may be frustration, and the staff will lose interest.
“If you are going to ask for 4,000 offers, you must be prepared to hold 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Rut, president of the management firm of Kotter International, who had to see companies make a mistake relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don't go to the end, the staff will wonder, ‘Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly staff interviews, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports the problem with the help of Glint.
And after collecting feedback from staff, dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is learning new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long run it will be able to better retain its staff in an industry known for high turnover.
“If you do not try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose clients.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
