Create a novel comic: One castle in English history
In the recent past, Scotty's tiny castle was filmed in a music video called "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 1980s served as a shelter for Margaret Thatcher.
But for 700 years from his cozy spot in the Bule Valley in Kent County, he watched a turbulent history around him, and now he inspired Jamie Rhodes, a yorkshire with a filthy hair and a tendency for historical documents, into a novel-comics.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says with enthusiasm.
"You feel it in person when you hold this letter in your hand."
The castle in England covers the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells about families who lived in Scotty; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists, Isaac Lenkevich, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer, and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not the first book of Rhoades, which is based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote "The Tooths of the Dead Man and Other Stories", a compilation of British Library documents; this project suddenly touched him deeply.
"I could have been touched by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites," he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those days there was a fire to light.
And in 300 years, in the future, you think you're there too.
Oh, I love archives!"
For a man so passionate about old papers, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and living in a castle for four months ("I've been there a little bit") seems too good to be true.
Rhoades spent all day studying the "new" Victorian castle, walking through the archives and looking at the many treasures of the property and the ancient things -- for example, the heads of the hyena on the walls or the bottles that lay in the hole for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talked to the foresters, the gardeners, and sometimes the artists who worked on the illustrations of his book.
Then at night, he "dranks whiskey and sits down to write."
The history of Scotty Castle is not well known, because the National Foundation only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassy, died.
When Rhoades arrived ten years later, the staff were just beginning to deal with an archival that he described as "what the aristocrats had fallen into the attic for centuries."
The journals, the letters of the British Empire, the maps showing who owned what you think land disputes are boring, Rhoades says, but two families fought for this berth.
It happens, guys!"
In some of the stories of the compilation, the castle becomes a starting point for broader research in English history: for example, in "The Workman", the hero leaves the castle just built to join the 1381 Crestian Revolution.
"There is evidence of a riot that occurred at the castle in 1380, in a book called "The knightly families of Kent and Sussex," Rhoades says.
"The Crusade Revolt began in these places, and I thought the riot was a good start.
Or were they bound together?"
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle, such as the Priest, which tells of the Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Smuggling" about an 18th-century smuggler, Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (which was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are the favorite family of Rhoades who lived in Scotty: "The Gentlemans seem to have been a perfect cheater, always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, the Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women -- I imagine them as a company of handsome guys who know how to care for the heirs of great fortunes."
After completing his work at the castle, Rhoades is looking for other opportunities to gain unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphical novel about Elyamyanmeaki, a place where there was a sanatorium at the beginning of the 20th century, and then it fell back into the woods.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt like, damn it, I have to go back to real life."
