The conflict within the ARB was initiated during a debate in the Federation Council, when new draft laws were considered by the Interregional Banking Council, including a reclassification of banks according to the size of statutory capital.
At that time, Garegin Tosunyan, President of the ARB, stated that the Association believed that the bill was being adopted for the benefit of the largest banks, which were thus trying to limit the capacity of small and medium-sized banks in the regions by intercepting their clients.
Other claims included criticism of the Central Bank, which, in Tosunyan's view, did not always justify the withdrawal of licences from some banks, which was, however, the subject of an objection by the representative of the CBG: many of the heads of the bank in question, such as the Veneshprombank, were part of the governing bodies of the ARB.
Apparently, this exchange of mutually exclusive views in a highly sensitive relationship with the main regulator of the banking environment has become a visible occasion for the 15 largest banks to start preparing themselves for joining the association “Russia”, noting that “the effectiveness of the work of the ARB will be low and constructive dialogue within the banking community is virtually non-existent”.
The depositors are better off.
