Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
However, recent studies suggest the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help to alleviate the symptoms of inflammable intestinal diseases.
It is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, leading to colicing and excrement, chronic or bloody diarrhea, loss of weight and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at Washington University have found that the main amino acid triptophane protein contributes to the production of immune cells that increase the tolerance of the intestines.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that the immune cells in the intestines ensure that harmful microbes coming in with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering inflammatory processes are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too disrupted towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory intestinal diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacteria in their intestines are developing more tolerant cells.
And this bacteria needs a triptophan, one of the building elements of a protein, to start the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We have established a connection between one bacteria species, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the normal microbiomy of the intestine, and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more the triptophane was contained in the mice's diet, the more these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work for humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a rich triptopane diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation in the intestines.
Postdock, Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganwas, studying a variety of tolerance-enhancing immune cells, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separate, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by microbial intestinal intestines -- communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestine cells has been sequented, and six species of bacteria have been found present in mice with immune cells but not in mice without them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiomy and did not develop this kind of immune cell received L. reuteri, and they developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then moved small portions of liquid -- without bacteria -- to undeveloped immune cells separated from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it was a by-product of triptophane treatment known as indol-3 milk acid.
When researchers doubled the number of triptophane in mice’s food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the triptophane level was halved, the number of cells also halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of the L. reuteri have contributed to the development of human cells as in mice, but people with inflammable intestinal diseases have been found to be defective in the genes associated with the triptophane.
She says, "Perhaps we need to increase the development of these cells, because these cells depend on inflammatory processes on the inside of the intestines.
High triptophane levels with L. reuteri may potentially lead to an increase in their population.”
