The White House bill cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to the records of the armed forces given to the magazine TIME, the White House's decision last month to bring a marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost the taxpayers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One", when the president is on board, became a central element of the 17 July White House event at which American construction programmes were shown.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and White House senior officials have been looking at the technology products from all 50 states.
A helicopter made in Connecticut was placed next to a boat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a cargo truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the unit responsible for the helicopter management, the White House Military Authority ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of a “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to make sure that you knew because this is an unusually publicized event,” wrote Commander HMX-1 in an e-mail to his chief, the first deputy aviation chief of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive in the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was released between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return in accordance with the working hours limits.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the course of the event, while the guard of the unit remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records received by the magazine, whether a second crew was required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal officials from using State property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the activity was in conflict with this regulation.
“We asked, among other things, whether it was a violation of Hatch's law, and they said no,” wrote the commander.
“You seem to have nowhere to go,” replied the Deputy Chief.
The "Making America" event was declared an official event by the White House and was not subject to the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the reform of the health care that had been drafted in the Senate at the time, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask for them alone in the interest of photofidelity.
Trump was already the subject of discussion in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during its first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was full of complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is thrilled with the "Make in America" show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” says the deputy secretary of the White House, Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often fly around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the President of the United States to transport to the White House to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 carried out 58 training landings at the White House.
One of the officials said that the flight carried out for the "Done in America" event was counted to the crew for the necessary training flights in a month.
The unit helicopters also overflew 11 additional hours on that day as part of “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, the taxpayers were not costed for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company did not participate in the South Lawn helicopter demonstration.
HMX-1 does not account for the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to Department of Defense hourly rates for the fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's VH-3D rate is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records that air time was 30 minutes each way from its airstrip at the Quantico Marine Airbase in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“The calculation of the cost for taxpayers, based on the approximate rate of reimbursement, is totally wrong,” says Walters.
“These indicative rates include personnel, services and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocations.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by the RAND Corporation, the rates of reimbursement do not include the cost of personnel, but indeed take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, the former White House spokesperson, Sean Spicer, spoke out to defend the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to show this week the things done in America,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose job depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
Therefore, of course, it is entirely appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter by inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely sitting in a driver's seat in a fire truck.
Within the White House, Trump approached Sikorsky's representatives, making a joke with the press about his own fleet of products.
"I know very well "Sikorsky," the president said. "I have three of them."
