The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company has been silent about the future investment in the Chicago facility.
More than 500 people work in a factory that produces, among other products, Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies.
Pladis, the owner of McVitie's, reports that over five million pounds have been invested in the facility over the past few years.
The company adds that, in the event of any change in the work of the facility, the employees and representatives of the union “are the first to know about them”.
In a letter to the head of the company's facility, the Scottish branch of GMB demanded that McVite's respond to the concern that funding would not be used to upgrade production lines.
Senior organizer Drew Duffy stated: “The members of our union are deeply concerned that we cannot obtain clarity from the CEO of the business needs and investment plan for the future of Tolcross.”
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is great in local society and in the Greater Glasgow territory; this is the most important pillar of decent work in high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, in terms of jobs, wages, and prosperity, and against the background of Brexit, the rise in the subsistence minimum and the chronic decline in production, the East End Glasgow is desperately in need of prosperity in the McVitie's factory.
According to the representative of Pladis, “the head of the Transversian site only yesterday received a letter from the Scottish branch of GMB, and the company will respond immediately, because we appreciate our continued cooperation with the staff and union representatives.”
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting in Tolcross with GMB staff and representatives, where we openly discussed a number of issues.
We talked to the staff about how, like all companies working in the most competitive and unstable economic environment, we are constantly reviewing our actions – and this concerns all our facilities and activities – to remain competitive.
“In recent years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in our Tkórósian facility, especially in production lines and improved functional performance.”
We are fully aware of the value of Tolcross as a production facility, and in the event of any change in the work at this site, the employees and representatives of the union will be the first to know.”
